# Mantine First in `web/`

- Use Mantine components, props, spacing, typography, and theming primitives before writing custom CSS.
- Prefer `Stack`, `Group`, `Container`, `Paper`, `Text`, `Title`, `Button`, `TextInput`, etc., instead of custom wrappers.
- Prefer Mantine style APIs (`c`, `bg`, `p`, `m`, `radius`, `w`, `h`, `visibleFrom`, `hiddenFrom`, `style` prop) over `.css` files.
- Add custom CSS only when Mantine cannot reasonably express the requirement (for example, very specific animation/keyframes or third-party integration edge cases).
- If custom CSS is needed:
  - keep it minimal and component-scoped;
  - document in a short comment why Mantine-only was not enough;
  - avoid global overrides unless strictly required.
- Keep dark/light behavior compatible with Mantine color scheme (`MantineProvider` + `ColorSchemeScript`).

## Quick Examples

```tsx
// Preferred (Mantine-first)
<Paper withBorder radius="md" p="md">
  <Stack gap="sm">
    <Title order={3}>Agentic Chat</Title>
    <TextInput placeholder="Write a message..." />
    <Button>Send</Button>
  </Stack>
</Paper>
```

```tsx
// Avoid by default (custom CSS-first)
<div className="chatCard">
  <h3>Agentic Chat</h3>
  <input className="chatInput" />
</div>
```
